Patients with musculoskeletal diseases and cognitive impairments often experience difficulties in movement and negative impacts on their mental well-being. Traditionally, clinical gait analysis relies on expensive technology, but recent advancements in computer vision and deep learning have led to more affordable alternatives. This study introduces a new approach that uses a spatial-temporal transformer network to estimate key gait parameters from video footage captured by a single camera. Experimental results on a public dataset of patients with cerebral palsy show that this framework outperforms current methods in predicting important gait metrics, such as walking speed, while requiring fewer inputs and eliminating the need for manual feature extraction.

Individuals with musculoskeletal conditions and cognitive impairments frequently encounter challenges in mobility and suffer from negative emotional consequences. This study presents a novel method that employs a spatial-temporal transformer network to estimate crucial gait metrics from video recordings taken by a single camera. Experimental findings on a publicly available dataset of patients with cerebral palsy demonstrate that this framework surpasses existing techniques in predicting vital gait metrics, such as walking pace, while requiring fewer inputs and eliminating the need for manual feature extraction.
